To solve this problem, let's use Java due to its widespread adoption and easy-to-understand syntax. Implementing a queue using two stacks involves using one stack for enqueuing elements and another for dequeuing them. When we need to dequeue an element, we reverse the order of the enqueue stack by popping all its elements and pushing them onto the dequeue stack, effectively turning the bottom of the enqueue stack into the top of the dequeue stack. 

Here is a basic implementation:

```java
import java.util.Stack;

public class QueueUsingStacks {
    private Stack<Integer> enqueueStack;
    private Stack<Integer> dequeueStack;

    public QueueUsingStacks() {
        enqueueStack = new Stack<>();
        dequeueStack = new Stack<>();
    }

    public void enqueue(int data) {
        enqueueStack.push(data);
    }

    public int dequeue() {
        if (dequeueStack.isEmpty()) {
            while (!enqueueStack.isEmpty()) {
                dequeueStack.push(enqueueStack.pop());
            }
        }
        return dequeueStack.isEmpty() ? -1 : dequeueStack.pop();
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return enqueueStack.isEmpty() && dequeueStack.isEmpty();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        QueueUsingStacks queue = new QueueUsingStacks();
        queue.enqueue(1);
        queue.enqueue(2);
        queue.enqueue(3);
        System.out.println(queue.dequeue());
        queue.enqueue(4);
        System.out.println(queue.dequeue());
    }
}
```

This implementation offers the `enqueue(int data)` method for adding elements to the queue and the `dequeue()` method for removing elements from the front of the queue. Note that the `dequeue` operation may require transferring all elements from the enqueue stack to the dequeue stack, giving it an amortized O(1) time complexity over a large number of operations.

To tackle this task, we'll provide solutions in both Java and C++. The key idea in checking for a palindrome is comparing characters from the start and end of the string towards the middle, ensuring that they are the same.

### Java Implementation:
```java
public class PalindromeCheck {
    public static boolean isPalindrome(String str) {
        int i = 0, j = str.length() - 1;
        while (i < j) {
            if (str.charAt(i) != str.charAt(j))
                return false;
            i++;
            j--;
        }
        return true;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "racecar"; // Example string
        System.out.println(str + " is a palindrome? " + isPalindrome(str));
    }
